Russia debates its future
JAROSLAWL: Russia, say many, lacks a “civil society”.
However, it makes up for this somewhat with an interesting public space in which serious topics are indeed debated and where fleeting glances at the powerful are not entirely limited to TV clips.
In the first two weeks of September, there were consecutive meetings of two important Russian political groups, the Valdai Discussion Club and the Global Policy Forum.
The former took place on a ship and ended with a dinner with Prime Minister Vladimir Putin in Sotschi at the Black Sea.
Lastly, in Yaroslavl, this culminated in a symposium with President Dmitry Medvedev.
Scientists, members of think tanks, and journalists (both Russian and foreign) discussed together with important politicians and business leaders about Russia's future.
Three things made these events in a typically Russian way something special.
The first was the intense media interest.
Even a scientist who was extremely camera-shy could suddenly find himself as a Russian TV star.
The second point was the readiness of both Putin and Medvedev to engage publicly with experts on their own intellectual terrain.
Only one Western political leader of recent times comes to mind who had the self-confidence to do this; that was Bill Clinton.
Finally, the two events marked the emergence of two rival political forums, each of which emitted the faint but unmistakable scent of a rising conflict.
For anyone with eyes in their head, these two conferences offered a fascinating insight into a crumbling diarchy.
The main theme of the Valdai Conference was whether Russia's history and geography condemned it to an authoritarian rule.
If democracy is to be the future, then is it Russia's fate to miss it?
The pessimists – above all Russian historians – argued that it would be difficult if not impossible for Russia to overcome its autocratic heritage.
Lew Beloussow of Moscow State University argued that autocracy rises in Russia – supported by the passivity and endurance of the Russians – again and again like a phoenix from the ashes.
The Bolsheviks had inherited autocracy from the Tsars; Putin rediscovered the old monarchical principle of the anointing of his successor and thus bypassed the democratic competition for the presidency.
Radicals like Wladimir Ryschkow rejected this historical determinism. According to Ryschkow, one should not legitimize authoritarianism by referring to history.
The protests were increasing.
It is the yoke of Putin, not that of history, that weighs heavily on Russia.
Many in this discussion lacked clarity, as is typically the case in discussions of this kind.
Most participants failed to distinguish between history as a constraint and history as a determinant.
Countries and civilizations can never overcome their history in its entirety, but every history offers many different possibilities.
Länder are not genetically programmed like animals.
The discussion about autocracy was inevitably linked to other topics.
One defended autocracy in Russia as necessary for a world empire.
However, this leads to another question: Does Russia need a world empire?
Can Russia renounce its imperial past and cultivate normal relations with its newly independent neighbors like Ukraine and Georgia?
Can it really be a completely "normal" actor on the world stage?
At the conference in Jaroslawl with Medvedev, attention shifted to the connection between democracy and modernization.
Everyone agreed that Russia had to diversify its economy and overcome its dependence on energy.
As Medvedev emphasized, an economy based on raw materials is always vulnerable to fluctuations in raw material prices.
However, there are roughly two views on the relationship between political and economic modernization.
Putin's view is that democracy results from a modern economy, as a kind of reward for hard work done.
If the state promotes modernization from above, democracy will grow naturally, albeit slowly, due to increasing prosperity and a growing middle class.
The Kremlin's chief ideologue, Vladislav Surkov, has suggested that genuine democracy requires a 'democracy in the head', thereby implying that this desirable mental state is still far away in Russia.
The alternative view, represented by people like Igor Yurgens, head of Medvedev's preferred think tank, the Institute of Contemporary Development, is that democracy is a prerequisite for economic modernization.
They argue that the Russian state in its current form lacks any genuine incentive to reform its own poor economic habits – or those of the Russians.
The development so far confirms this.
Russia has laid down a modest recovery from the recession.
Yet there is almost no innovation; the elites are content with enjoying a comfortable life with the profits from the energy business, and corruption continues unchecked.
Putin is the strong leader of a weak state, which, lacking a mobilizing element or feedback process, is unable to carry out a modernization project.
There is a clear gap between Putin and Medvedev.
Medwedew is anything but Putin's puppet.
Both believe that democracy must come sooner or later, but with Putin the emphasis is clearly on "later," while Medwedew has added a liberating voice to the public discourse in Russia.
Cynics claim that this is merely a misleading routine following the motto "good cop, bad cop."
But words count, and a new rhetoric is a political force of its own.
Medwedew's main strategic goal must now be to secure a second term as President.
He can't openly question Putin's legacy, but he has to position himself as someone who goes beyond Putin.
It's a challenging balancing act, because Putin can reclaim the presidency at any time if he thinks his former protégé wants to dismantle the authoritarian state that Putin created.
19 years after the fall of communism, Russia's direction is still unclear, as it has always been.
This is particularly important for the Russians, but since Russia spans the enormous Eurasian landmass, the lack of clarity about Russia's future poses a constant concern for the rest of us.
Is Russia part of the West?
Give him his history and geography an unmistakably Eurasian perspective, capable of smoothing out a potential collision between Western and Eastern civilizations, or between Christianity and Islam?
Russia cannot be neatly categorized into geopolitical categories, but it remains too important to ignore.
